"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386981","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-06","<p /> <p>In December 2014 DWP published a suite of evaluation reports available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/benefit-cap-evaluation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/benefit-cap-evaluation</a>. These found very little, if any, impact on homelessness as a direct result of the cap. The small number of capped households who have been evicted were noted by Local Authorities as having other reasons (beyond the cap) for rent arrears and also failing to engage with relevant services; they were considered intentionally homeless.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-07-06T13:44:13.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386981/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386981/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386981/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-01","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of the benefit cap on levels of homelessness in each year since its introduction.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","5105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386982","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-07","<p>I refer my hon. Friend to the Written Ministerial Statement made on 18 June, HCWS42, which is the most up to date expression of planning policy for onshore wind energy development.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","5089 ; 5090","2015-07-07T14:11:15.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386982/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386982/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386982/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-01","Wind Power: Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether the National Planning Policy Framework for onshore wind projects of under 50MW takes precedence over new considerations to be applied to proposed wind energy developments issued on 18 June 2015.","false","Biography information for Nigel Huddleston","Mid Worcestershire","Nigel Huddleston","5088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386983","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-06","<p>My rt. hon. Friend, the Secretary of State is already considering this request.<br><br>The local authority has been informed of this request and it is a matter for them to decide how this should inform their planning decision making process, including the forthcoming committee.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-07-06T15:18:41.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386983/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386983/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386983/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-01","Housing: Headcorn","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will request Maidstone Borough Council to require the applicant to carry out an Environmental Impact Assessment for the proposed development at Hazelpits Farm, Headcorn (Application Ref: 15/503325/Hybrid) prior to the determination by Maidstone Borough Council's planning committee planned for 9 July 2015.","false","Biography information for Helen Whately","Faversham and Mid Kent","Helen Whately","5183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386984","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-06","<p>I have made no assessment. My officials are in regular contact with the ER2015 about ticket sales, including the secondary market.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","5244","2015-07-06T16:21:24.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386984/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386984/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386984/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-01","Rugby: World Cup","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate his Department has made of the number of tickets for the 2015 Rugby World Cup available on the secondary market.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","5243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386985","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-06","<p>I have made no assessment. My officials are in regular contact with the ER2015 about ticket sales, including the secondary market.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","5243","2015-07-06T16:21:24.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386985/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386985/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386985/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-01","Rugby: World Cup","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the average price of a ticket for the 2015 Rugby World Cup bought from the secondary market.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","5244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386986","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-10","<p>Stakeholders which have expressed their support include: the British Council, British Museum, the Victoria and Albert Museum, UNESCO, UK National Committee of the Blue Shield, British Institute for the Study of Iraq and the Council for British Archaeology among others.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will be leading discussions with key cultural stakeholders as part of the process of the development of the cultural protection fund.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-10T11:34:39.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386986/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386986/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386986/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-01","Cultural Heritage: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 20 June 2015 to Question 3292 on creating a cultural protection fund, which key cultural organisations agree that this measure is needed.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","5196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386987","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-10","<p>The public library statistics published by the Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy in December 2014 included for the first time a breakdown of the different ways in which communities are involved with their local public library service for each of the local authorities in England. A copy of the annual report is placed in the House Library. However, libraries run by volunteers also operate outside of the public library service provided by local authorities and as previously indicated, the Department does not collect data on their number.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The responsibility of the Secretary of State under the Public Libraries and Museums Act 1964 is to superintend, and promote the improvement of, the public library service provided by local authorities in England and secure the proper discharge by local authorities of their duty to provide a comprehensive and efficient public library service. This responsibility does not extend to libraries which operate outside of the public library service provided by local authorities and for this reason information is not collected. To do so would require the initial and on-going input of 151 local authorities in England, as well as contributions from other sources and analysis of the robustness of the data.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-10T11:39:02.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386987/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386987/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386987/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-01","Public Libraries: Voluntary Work","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 20 June 2015 to Question 3288, for what reasons he is not able to estimate the cost of collecting information on the number of volunteer-run libraries.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","5198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386988","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-06","<p>Further to my answer to Question 3327, it was considered impractical to release the list because it was drawn from out of date information held from April 2015. DCMS has since received new data which is being incorporated into the list of public libraries without Wifi and a copy will be placed in the Library of the House in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-06T14:43:53.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386988/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386988/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386988/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-01","Public Libraries: WiFi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 29 June 2015 to Question 3327, on public libraries: wifi, for what reasons it is impractical to place his current list in the Library.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","5223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386989","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-06","<p>My Department will be conducting a public consultation later this year which will contain a number of proposals relating to the definition of Treasure and other measures set out in the Treasure Code of Practice. The Government's response to the consultation will be published thereafter.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-06T08:12:12.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386989/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386989/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386989/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-01","Treasure Act 1996","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when he plans to review the Treasure Act 1996.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","5202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386990","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-06","<p>The 2015-16 resource allocation given to the British Museum by my Department includes funding for the administration of the Portable Antiquities Scheme and allows the British Museum to determine how the Scheme is resourced within its overall funding settlement. The Portable Antiquities Scheme, which recorded its one millionth find in 2013, continues to be a hugely valuable resource which broadens our understanding of history and archaeology and allows full public engagement with the process. I have made no assessment of the impact that the changes in funding arrangements have had on the Scheme as I believe it is right that the British Museum has more freedom to make its own decisions on spending in this area.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-06T08:15:10.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386990/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386990/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386990/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-01","Portable Antiquities Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the continued viability of the Portable Antiquities Scheme after changes to its funding by the British Museum.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","5203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386991","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-10","<p>The Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport announced on 21<sup>st</sup> June that the Government is developing a new cultural protection fund that will support the protection of cultural heritage of countries affected by conflict or at risk of coming under attack for ideological reasons. The Government will bring forward legislation to allow ratification of the Hague Convention at the earliest opportunity.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-10T11:45:42.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386991/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386991/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-01","Cultural Heritage: Middle East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to help protect cultural sites in the Middle East.","false","Biography information for Alison McGovern","Wirral South","Alison McGovern","5151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386992","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-10","<p>Work is underway to develop a cultural protection fund and my Department will be bringing together key organisations to advise on how the fund will be delivered.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-10T13:18:32.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386992/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386992/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386992/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-01","Cultural Heritage: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress he has made on establishing a cultural protection fund.","false","Biography information for Alison McGovern","Wirral South","Alison McGovern","5152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386993","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-10","<p>Work on establishing the Cultural Protection Fund is underway.</p><p> </p><p>The overall level of exchequer funding for the cultural protection fund will be determined by the forthcoming Spending Review process.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-10T13:26:22.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386993/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386993/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386993/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-01","Cultural Heritage: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will estimate the cost to the public purse of establishing a cultural protection fund.","false","Biography information for Alison McGovern","Wirral South","Alison McGovern","5153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386994","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-10","<p>I have not had such discussions yet. As part of the 800MHz spectrum auction Telefonica has a licence condition requiring them to deliver 4G coverage to 98% of UK premises (and a minimum of 95% of premises in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland) by 2017. Other mobile network operators have publicly stated an intention to match this coverage, so consumers should benefit from greater choice and greater coverage. Ofcom’s Infrastructure Report shows that as of June 2014 44% of premises in Wales had 4G coverage and 79% of Wales received 3G coverage.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-10T11:49:28.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386994/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386994/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386994/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-01","4G: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions he has had with (a) the Secretary of State for Wales and (b) Ministers in the Welsh Government on the roll-out of 4G mobile telephone coverage in rural areas in Wales.","false","Biography information for Albert Owen","Ynys Môn","Albert Owen","5121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386995","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-06","<p>Airworthiness in relation to whether an aircraft is legally safe to fly is my responsibility as Minister for Defence Procurement. Aircraft accidents are the responsibility of the Minister of State for the Armed Forces. The Defence Safety Authority (which has subsumed the Military Aircraft Authority) is now the responsibility of the Minister for Defence Personnel and Veterans.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-07-06T15:22:20.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386995/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386995/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386995/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-01","Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, under which Minister in his Department responsibility for military airworthiness lies.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","5144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386996","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-06","<p>The total cost of repairs required at Bassingbourn Barracks was £138,000, this work has been completed and paid for by the Ministry of Defence. The costs are currently being recovered from the Libyan Government.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","5231","2015-07-06T15:42:03.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386996/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386996/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386996/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-01","Military Bases: Bassingbourn","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 24 June 2015 to Question 2850, what estimate he has made of the total cost of repairs to be paid for by the Libyan government following the Libyan training mission at Bassingbourn base; what payments in respect of those repairs have been made by that government; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","5131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386997","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-09","<p>The total costs to the Ministry of Defence of the Libyan training at Bassingbourn in 2014 was £14 million for the training delivered between April and September 2014 and £3 million for the reactivation of Bassingbourn Camp.</p><p>£2.48 million was received from the Libyan government for the reactivation of Bassingbourn. £65,000 was received for the payment of allowances to the trainees and a total of £195,500 was received for the cost of commercial and charter flights to return the trainees at the end of the training.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-07-09T15:03:58.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386997/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386997/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386997/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-01","Libya: Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the (a) total and (b) set up costs of the Libyan training mission at Bassingbourn base were; what payments have been made by the Libyan government to cover (i) activation costs, (ii) flights, (iii) repairs, (iv) training, (v) facilities management and catering, (vi) infrastructure inventory and consumable items, (vii) personal costs, (viii) policing and (ix) transport; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","5130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386998","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-06","<p>No investment has been made at Bassingbourn Barracks since handover of the Barracks to the Defence Infrastructure Organisation in January 2013.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-07-06T15:26:39.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386998/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386998/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386998/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-01","Military Bases: Bassingbourn","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 24 June 2015 to Question 2855, how much the Defence Infrastructure Organisation has spent on Bassingbourn barracks since January 2013; what the nature and cost was of each improvement so funded at that barracks in that time period; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","5132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386999","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-06","<p>As per my answer on 3 March 2015 to Question 219659, the Ministry of Defence based Libyan personnel at Bassingbourn because it offered the required facilities for training and did not affect wider UK military training. As part of the preparation of Bassingbourn for training, security improvements were carried out, such as fencing off areas of the camp from local residences. The Army also held rehearsal meetings at Bassingbourn to identify and coordinate the mitigation of risks, including with the Home Office and the police. The Department has also met with Cambridge City Council following the termination of the training to discuss the findings of the report, and has written to them on a number of occasions.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-07-06T15:45:38.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386999/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386999/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386999/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-01","Libya: Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 22 June 2015 to Question 3418, on Libya: military training, where in the Answer of 3 March 2015 to Question 219659 the response to Question 3418 is contained; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","5147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387000","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-06","<p>The total cost of repairs required at Bassingbourn Barracks was £138,000, this work has been completed and paid for by the Ministry of Defence. The costs are currently being recovered from the Libyan Government.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","5131","2015-07-06T15:42:03.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387000/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387000/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387000/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-01","Military Bases: Bassingbourn","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 24 June 2015 to Question 2850, what estimate he has made of the cost of repairs required following the Libyan training mission at Bassingbourn base; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","5231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387001","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-09","<p>RAF personnel based at Leuchars will be replaced by the Royal Scots Dragoon Guards from summer 2015. This decision is based on the interests of the defence of the whole of the United Kingdom, rather than on the basis of the impact on a specific region.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-07-09T15:25:41.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387001/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387001/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387001/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-01","RAF Leuchars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the effect on the local economy of the departure of RAF personnel from Leuchars.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","5095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387002","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-06","<p>We have committed to maintaining the size of the regular Armed Forces, and we will continue to ensure we have the right mix of people and skills to deliver our world-leading defence capabilities.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-07-06T15:14:11.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387002/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387002/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387002/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-01","Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, What his policy is on the size of the regular armed forces.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","5069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387003","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-06","<p>The Ministry of Defence has made an estimate of both the unit and total cost of the UK's F-35B programme but does not release these costs as to do so could undermine its commercial position. These estimates are under constant review and updated as information is provided by the US programme.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-07-06T15:21:13.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387003/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387003/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387003/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-01","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of the (a) total cost and (b) number of units that will be produced by the F-35B aircraft programme.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","5066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387004","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-06","<p>The current forecast cost of the UK A400M aircraft acquisition programme is £2.75 billion, as reported in the Major Projects Report 2014.</p><p>This amount represents the expected cost of the programme to deliver the 22 A400M Atlas aircraft ordered by the RAF and encompasses some necessary costs (including, for example, safety, certification and airworthiness activities) in addition to the actual price of individual aircraft.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-07-06T15:22:50.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387004/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387004/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387004/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-01","Future Large Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of the unit costs of the A400M aircraft.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","5067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387005","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-06","<p>The Ministry of Defence has made an estimate of the unit cost of the UK's F-35B but does not release this data as to do so could undermine its commercial position. These estimates are under constant review and are updated as information is provided by the US programme. A generic and publically releasable estimate is published by the US Department of Defense within the annual selected acquisition reports for the Joint Strike Fighter programme.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-07-06T15:14:39.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387005/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387005/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387005/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-01","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of the unit costs of the F-35B aircraft.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","5068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387006","Department for Education","false","2015-07-08","<p>The review will consider the overall cost of providing childcare places. It will inform government decisions about funding for both the existing entitlement and the extension to 30 hours.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-07-08T10:00:01.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387006/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387006/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387006/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-01","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans for the funding rate review for the Government's proposal to provide 30 hours free childcare for three and four year olds to review the rate applicable for (a) all 30 hours or (b) the additional 15 hours.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","5075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387007","Department for Education","false","2015-07-08","<p>Supporting local authorities to create school places where they are needed most is one of the Department’s top priorities. In the last Parliament we spent £5 billion on capital funding for new school places, more than double what was spent between 2007-2011. In this Parliament we have committed £7 billion in capital funding between 2015 and 2021 to help local authorities create places. Local authorities will want to consider the specific challenges facing schools in rural areas when planning new school places.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-07-08T15:16:30.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387007/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387007/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387007/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-01","Primary Education: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to work with local authorities to support the expansion of over-subsidised rural primary schools.","false","Biography information for Edward Argar","Charnwood","Edward Argar","5077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387008","Department for Education","false","2015-07-09","<p>The Department for Education takes any failure to deliver services at the required level extremely seriously. The department is currently considering all the available evidence in order to act in a way which provides sustainable improvements for the children of Sandwell, ensuring that the services received by children, young people and their families improve to the required level.</p><p> </p><p>The department believes that Sandwell has had sufficient time to make the necessary improvements. Sandwell was originally rated as ‘inadequate’ by Ofsted in January 2010. During the five years in which Sandwell has been subject to intervention arrangements, a large number of local authorities have managed to improve their services to meet the required standard.</p><p>The department currently intervenes in 20 local authorities in which children’s social care services have been identified by Ofsted as failing children and young people. The interventions include a range of strategies, from enhanced oversight by department officials, independent advisors or commissioners, through to more extreme cases which have required the department to remove services from the local authority’s control. The level of support provided will depend on the scale of the issues identified by Ofsted and the capacity of the authority to address them.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","5091 ; 5092 ; 5093","2015-07-09T16:53:11.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387008/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387008/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387008/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-01","Children: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her Department is doing to ensure children's services rated as inadequate can be improved and begin to achieve their targets.","false","Biography information for James Morris","Halesowen and Rowley Regis","James Morris","5094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387009","Department for Education","false","2015-07-07","<p>Local authorities have clear duties to support children with special educational needs (SEN). They are responsible for planning and delivering the necessary services for children within their area.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Children and Families Act enables a joined-up approach to support children with sensory impairments, with clear information on the support that families can expect locally and the option of a personal budget for some parents and young people to give them control over the support they receive.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education funds the National Sensory Impairment Partnership (NatSIP) to support local authorities to benchmark and improve the support available for children with sensory impairments. NatSIP is working with sensory support services across the country to support the SEN reforms. NatSIP helps local authorities and settings ensure that the right support is in place to improve the outcomes for deaf, blind and multi-sensory impaired children.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-07-07T16:29:28.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387009/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387009/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387009/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-01","Hearing Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make it her policy to provide more funding for deaf people to procure the services of interpreters.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","5055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387010","Department for Education","false","2015-07-06","<p>We do not expect there to be any cost to the public purse as a result of the one year delay in Parkfield School being able to move to the new site at Hurn.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Education Funding Agency first became aware that the Hurn site is a habitat for bats in June 2015. A full site bat survey was not undertaken prior to the purchase of the Hurn site for Parkfield School as these are usually undertaken by contractors as part of the design and planning permission process.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Initial findings indicate that the Common Pipistrelle bat is the emergent species. Local activity of Soprano Pipistrelle and Noctule bats has also been observed.</p><p> </p><p>The bat surveys were undertaken as soon as it became evident they were necessary and completed last week. The survey information is currently being analysed and the final results of the surveys are expected in the next few weeks. An application to Natural England for bat removal licences will be made after planning approval is granted. Subject to planning approval the licences could be available towards the end of this year. Bat boxes will then be provided at agreed locations across the site prior to the demolition works commencing.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","5049 ; 5050","2015-07-06T16:08:13.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387010/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387010/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387010/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-01","Parkfield School Christchurch","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the estimated cost to the public purse is of the one year delay in Parkfield School being able to move to a new site at Hurn; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","5048"
