curate and complete. However, it is important to note that these data have been extracted from large administrative data systems generated by the courts and police forces. As a consequence, care should be taken to ensure data collection processes and their inevitable limitations are taken into account when those data are used.</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="7"><p>(3) Excludes data for Cardiff magistrates' court for April, July and August 2008.</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="7"><p>(4) The proportion of offenders sentenced who are sentenced to immediate custody.</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="6"><p>Source: Justice Statistics Analytical Services - Ministry of Justice.</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Ref: PQ 4826 </strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>These figures refer to offences of assaulting a police constable in the execution of his or her duty. More serious assaults against police officers charged under different offences are therefore not included.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-07-08T15:57:04.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386742/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386742/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-30","Assaults on Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people were convicted of assaulting a police officer in each of the last 10 years; and what proportion of such people received a prison sentence.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","4826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386743","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-08","<p>The Government is committed to reducing the supply of drugs into prison. The National Offender Management Service (NOMS) already deploys a comprehensive range of robust searching and security measures to detect items of contraband both at the point of entry to the prison and concealed within the prison. We do not tolerate drugs in prison and anyone caught with them will be punished and could face further prosecution.</p><p> </p><p>The success of the strategy is illustrated by the reduction of drug misuse in prisons, as measured by the random Mandatory Drug Testing (MDT) programme, which has declined by 17.5 percentage points over the past 17 years, despite the fact that NOMS is testing for more drugs than previously. Positive rates were 7.8% in 2009/2010 and 6.9% in 2014/2015.</p><p> </p><p>NOMS is aware of the increase of the use of New Psychoactive Substances (NPS) across the prison estate and there is a wide-ranging programme of work being undertaken to counteract NPS. This includes joint work with the Home Office on legislation to control most NPS substances and make it illegal to supply any NPS. This will allow prisons to press for the prosecution of those smuggling NPS into prisons. Additionally, work is underway to develop new drug tests to detect NPS substances, to strengthen perimeter defences, and to train drug dogs to detect NPS.</p><p> </p><p>We have already made it a criminal offence to throw drugs and other items over prison walls and the government's proposed new legislation will further strengthen our powers. We have also included a clause within the Serious Crime Act, which will create an offence of throwing or projecting any item over a prison perimeter so that it lands in a prison</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to explore new methods of preventing drugs coming into prisons such as new generation body scanners. The first body scanner has been purchased and a programme of work is underway to assess the most effective way to deploy body scanners across the estate, based on experience of their use in an operational setting. NOMS will be supported in this by the Home Office Centre for Applied Science and Technology. <br></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-07-08T15:35:22.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386743/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386743/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-30","Prisons: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent steps he has taken to reduce offenders' access to drugs in prisons.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","4864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386744","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-07","<p>There were no convictions under the Conservation of Seals Act 1970 or Article 3 of the Seal Products Regulations 2010 in England and Wales from 2011 to 2014. Therefore no fines were issued.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>However, this relates to prosecutions where these offences were the principal ones. When a defendant has been found guilty of two or more offences, the offence selected is the offence for which the statutory maximum penalty is the most severe. Therefore, the figures may not fully reflect the number of offences committed under legislation to protect seals.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","4946 ; 4989","2015-07-07T09:48:22.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386744/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386744/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-30","Conservation of Seals Act 1970","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many people have been convicted of offences under (a) section 1, (1), (b), section 2, (c) section 3 and (d) section 8 of the Conservation of Seals Act 1970 in each of the last four years; and how many of those convicted were fined the maximum amount stipulated for those offences.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","4890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386745","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-08","<p>Yes. Applications can be made under the Victims of Overseas Terrorism Compensation Scheme 2012 in relation to victims injured, or the families of those killed, in the attack. The Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority, which administers the scheme, has set up a major incident team which will process applications from those affected by this horrific event.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-07-08T10:48:38.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386745/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386745/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-30","Terrorism: Tunisia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether he plans to provide assistance to victims of the Tunisian attack on 26 June 2015 under the Victims of Overseas Terrorism Compensation Scheme 2012.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","4786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386746","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-14","<p>I refer to the answer to PQ 3772 - the MoJ does not hold information on the number of states party to the European Convention on Human Rights whose prisons breach any term of the Convention. However, information on states party to the European Convention on Human Rights, whose prisons have caused them to be found to be in violation of the Convention by the European Court of Human Rights, can be found on the Court’s searchable database at:</p><p><a title="http://hudoc.echr.coe.int/sites/eng/Pages/search.aspx#%7B%22documentcollectionid2%22:[%22GRANDCHAMBER%22,%22CHAMBER%22]%7D http://hudoc.echr.coe.int/sites/eng/Pages/search.aspx#{%22documentcollectionid2%22:[%22GRANDCHAMBER%22,%22CHAMBER%22]}" href="http://hudoc.echr.coe.int/sites/eng/Pages/search.aspx#%7B%22documentcollectionid2%22:[%22GRANDCHAMBER%22,%22CHAMBER%22]%7D" target="_blank">http://hudoc.echr.coe.int/sites/eng/Pages/search.aspx#{%22documentcollectionid2%22:[%22GRANDCHAMBER%22,%22CHAMBER%22]}</a></p><p>Where the European Court of Human Rights has ruled that poor prison conditions in a state party to the Convention breach the requirements of the Convention, the government would seek to find a way to enable the transfer to take place through assurances or other measures to address that issue. We have not yet had to seek such an assurance nor have we refused a transfer based on the grounds that prison conditions breach article 3.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2015-07-14T10:17:00.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386746/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386746/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-30","Offenders: Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent information he holds on the number of states party to the European Convention on Human Rights whose prisons breach any term of that convention; and what recent assessment he has made of the effect of such breaches on the deportation of people from the UK to prisons in (a) EU and (b) non-EU countries.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","4764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386747","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-06","<p>We are alert to the risks posed by individuals who may wish to radicalise others, and we are committed to tackling radicalisation in prisons as an important element of our responsibility to protect the public and reduce re-offending.</p><p> </p><p>NOMS has in place a wide-ranging programme of work to identify and manage the risks of extremism and radicalisation amongst offenders, which includes intelligence management and sharing, staff training and offender management and interventions.</p><p> </p><p>NOMS contributes to the cross-Government Counter Terrorism Strategy CONTEST, and works with Law Enforcement Agency partners and alongside other Departments to manage the threat posed. <br></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-07-06T15:24:21.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386747/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386747/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-30","Prisoners: Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he is taking to tackle prisoners being radicalised by religious extremism; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","4757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386748","Leader of the House","false","2015-07-06","<p>The assessment was made on the basis of the impact of the legislation, rather than their territorial extent. The proposals that I announced on 2 July on English Votes for English Laws provide for a straightforward test, based firmly on the devolution settlement.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2015-07-06T16:05:25.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386748/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386748/answer",,,,,,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-06-30","Government Bills","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, pursuant to the Answer of 30 June 2015 to Question 4228, what criteria he used to determine whether the legislation in question affected a particular country or combination of countries.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","5037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386749","Leader of the House","false","2015-07-06","<p>The following Government bills introduced in the last Parliament affected (a) England only and (b) England and Wales only. No account was taken in this assessment of any minor or consequential effects.</p><p><strong><br></strong>a) England only<strong><br></strong></p><p>Education</p><p>b) England and Wales only</p><p>Local Government Finance</p><p>Charities</p><p>Local Government</p><p>Scotland</p><p>Police (Detention and Bail)</p><p>Sunday Trading (London and Olympic Games and Paralympic Games)</p><p>Water Industry (Financial Assistance)</p><p>Defamation</p><p>Mental Health (Approval Functions)</p><p>Criminal Justice and Courts</p><p>Local Audit and Accountability</p><p>Rehabilitation</p><p>Modern Slavery</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2015-07-06T16:02:12.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386749/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386749/answer",,,,,,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-06-30","Government Bills","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, pursuant to the Answer of 30 June 2015 to Question 4228, which bills affect (a) England only and (b) England and Wales only.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","5035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386750","Leader of the House","false","2015-07-06","<p>All Government bills introduced in the 5 years of the last Parliament included provisions which extended to Wales with the exception of the Partnerships (Prosecution) (Scotland) Bill (2012-13 Session).</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2015-07-06T16:04:20.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386750/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386750/answer",,,,,,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-06-30","Government Bills","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, which Government bills have been introduced with provisions which extended to Wales in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","5036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386751","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-07-07","<p>This issue has not been raised with me by Executive Ministers.</p><p>The Competition and Markets Authority has investigated the private motor insurance market across the UK including Northern Ireland and published its final report in September 2014. Measures to be introduced include a ban on agreements between price comparison websites and insurers which prevent insurers making their products available more cheaply elsewhere.</p><p>In March 2015, the Competition and Markets Authority published its final Order setting out how changes resulting from its investigation will be introduced.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2015-07-07T09:50:48.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386751/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386751/answer",,,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-06-30","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions she has had with Ministers in the Northern Ireland Executive on measures to bring the level of car insurance premiums in Northern Ireland in line with those in the rest of the UK; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","4853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386752","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-08","<p>Under the Code of Practice for Ministerial Appointments to Public Bodies April 2012, government departments are required to publicise successful appointments.</p><p>No public appointments were made by the Scotland Office between 1 January 2015 and 1 May 2015.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-07-08T12:07:14.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386752/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386752/answer",,,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-30","Scotland Office: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, if he will place in the Library a list of all public appointments made by his Department between 1 January 2015 and 1 May 2015.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","4971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386753","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-06","<p>My answer of 30 June 2015 to question 3377 covered the content of my meeting with the Secretary of State for Transport. Included in the discussion on the benefits to Scotland of HS2 was the current estimates that suggest the Scottish Economy will benefit by around £3bn.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-07-06T15:06:45.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386753/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386753/answer",,,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-30","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, pursuant to the Answer of 30 June 2015 to Question 3377 on High Speed 2 railway line: Scotland, what the content of the discussion at that meeting was.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart McDonald","4750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386754","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-06","<p>Advice has been prepared by HS2 Ltd in conjunction with the UK Government and the Scottish Government to identify broad options for high speed and upgraded railways to the north of England and Scotland. This is currently under consideration by Ministers and will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-07-06T15:07:59.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386754/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386754/answer",,,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-30","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what assessment the Government has made of the potential merits of the (a) High Speed 2 line extending to Scotland and (b) construction of that line beginning in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart McDonald","4751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386755","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-06","<p>I have regular meetings with Ministerial colleagues on a range of issues including opportunities to promote Scotland. I plan to meet the Minister of State for Trade and Investment shortly to discuss trade and investment opportunities.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-07-06T15:09:36.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386755/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386755/answer",,,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-30","Overseas Trade: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, when he last met the Minister of State for Trade and Investment to discuss trade and investment opportunities for Scotland.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","4734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386756","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-06","<p>UKTI leads a wide programme of engagement to promote opportunities for UK companies in North America. I will be working with Scottish business leaders over the coming months to consider options for specific trade and investment engagement in North America.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-07-06T15:10:46.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386756/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386756/answer",,,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-30","Trade Promotion: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what plans he has to lead trade and investment missions for Scottish companies to North America.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","4735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386757","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-06","<p>UKTI leads a wide programme of engagement to promote opportunities for UK companies in Asia. I will be working with Scottish business leaders over the coming months to consider options for specific trade and investment engagement during the life of this parliament.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-07-06T15:11:48.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386757/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386757/answer",,,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-30","Trade Promotion: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what plans he has to lead trade and investment missions for Scottish companies to Asia.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","4736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386758","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-06","<p>UKTI and SDI work in partnership to promote Scotland as a location for trade and investment. The Scotland Office will work with both UKTI and SDI to take forward the recommendations raised in the Wilson Review of support for Scottish Exporting.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-07-06T15:12:57.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386758/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386758/answer",,,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-30","Trade Promotion: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, if he will publish a strategy for the promotion of Scotland as a location for trade and investment.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","4737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386759","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2015-07-06","<p>The eligibility criteria for emergency proxy votes are set out in legislation, and are therefore a matter for the UK and Scottish governments and their respective parliaments.</p><p> </p><p>The Electoral Commission continues to recommend that the UK and Scottish governments should extend the eligibility criteria for appointing an emergency proxy to include those who have unforeseen caring responsibilities or who have experienced the death of a close relative, and will reiterate this recommendation in its report on the May 2015 elections.</p><p> </p>","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter",,"2015-07-06T14:08:43.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386759/answer","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386759/answer",,,,,,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2015-06-30","Absent Voting","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for South West Devon, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, if the Commission will extend eligibility for emergency proxy votes to healthy people who are unable to vote because they need to be with a family member who is undergoing medical treatment.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","4886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386760","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-06","<p>In the last six months I have not held any meetings with Network Rail’s Chief Executive at which no official was present.</p><p> </p>","Derbyshire Dales","Mr Patrick McLoughlin",,"2015-07-06T16:17:38.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386760/answer","Biography information for Sir Patrick McLoughlin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386760/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Network Rail: Meetings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, on what dates in the last six months he has held meetings with the chief executive of Network Rail at which officials were not present.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","4921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386761","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-08","<p>Through the Northern Hub project, the Department assessed the effects of enabling faster, more direct and more frequent services to be operated between many places across the north of England, and of the capacity to accommodate more passengers at peak times. In the Business Case for the Northern Hub the project as a whole was assessed to bring £4 billion worth of wider benefits to the region and potentially 20,000 to 30,000 new jobs.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, the recently issued invitations to tender for the next Northern and Transpennine Express rail franchises mark an important step in the transformation of the train services in the north of England to support economic growth, and this includes a modernised fleet of Northern trains, including full replacement of the unpopular Pacers and the introduction of 120 new-build vehicles by 2020.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-07-08T07:20:00.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386761/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386761/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment the Government has made of the effect of the electrification of the Transpennine rail route on (a) economic growth and (b) job creation in each affected region.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","4843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386762","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-08","<p>The Department is continuing to develop its response to the Law Commission’s recommendations on the reform of level crossing legislation in conjunction with stakeholders.</p><p> </p><p>Our Level Crossing Reform Action Plan, copies of which are available in the House library, explains the steps that we are taking and includes an indicative timetable for completion of this process.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-07-08T07:35:57.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386762/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386762/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Level Crossings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what changes he plans to make to level crossings.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","4844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386763","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-07","<p>Taxi and private hire vehicle licensing, including taxi fare regulation, is carried out by local licensing authorities. They have no power to determine private hire vehicle fares or prescribe how they are calculated. Private hire fares are set by licensed operators and when booking a private hire vehicle, customers can obtain a quote or estimate for a journey in advance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Law Commission has recently completed a comprehensive review of taxi and private hire legislation and recommended retention of the current system for setting taxi and private hire vehicle fares. The Government is currently considering the Law Commission report and will provide a full response in due course.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-07-07T14:29:03.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386763/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386763/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Taxis: Fares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the implications for the effect in regulation of taxi and minicab companies of increasing use of smartphone technology to calculate fares; and whether he plans to introduce legislation on that matter.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","4841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386764","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-08","<p>The following table shows estimated government capital expenditure on railways and local public transport per head of population in each region of England between 2009/10 and 2013/14, the latest year for which figures are available.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><p><strong>Government capital expenditure on railways and local public transport per head of population</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Region</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> 2009/10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> 2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> 2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> 2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> 2013/14</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North East</p></td><td><p>£60</p></td><td><p>£65</p></td><td><p>£60</p></td><td><p>£64</p></td><td><p>£73</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>£105</p></td><td><p>£119</p></td><td><p>£115</p></td><td><p>£104</p></td><td><p>£118</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorkshire &amp; Humber</p></td><td><p>£69</p></td><td><p>£67</p></td><td><p>£77</p></td><td><p>£79</p></td><td><p>£80</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>£42</p></td><td><p>£40</p></td><td><p>£53</p></td><td><p>£44</p></td><td><p>£45</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>£64</p></td><td><p>£63</p></td><td><p>£66</p></td><td><p>£77</p></td><td><p>£88</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East of England</p></td><td><p>£63</p></td><td><p>£60</p></td><td><p>£66</p></td><td><p>£63</p></td><td><p>£66</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>£358</p></td><td><p>£327</p></td><td><p>£288</p></td><td><p>£237</p></td><td><p>£268</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>£77</p></td><td><p>£76</p></td><td><p>£68</p></td><td><p>£67</p></td><td><p>£66</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>£50</p></td><td><p>£48</p></td><td><p>£43</p></td><td><p>£44</p></td><td><p>£43</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>England</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£113</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£110</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£104</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£96</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£104</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Source: HMT, ONS</p></td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>These estimates are based on the Public Expenditure Statistical Analyses (PESA) published by the Treasury. The methods used to allocate expenditure between countries and regions may be subject to changes over time, so changes from year to year may reflect differences in methodology rather than real changes.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>Expenditure is usually allocated between regions on the basis of which regions benefit from the expenditure rather than on the basis of where the expenditure is made. However, it is not always possible to put the value of spending down to certain parts of the country on a ‘who benefits’ basis and this is particularly a problem for spending on motorways and trunk roads (by Highways England) and on the rail network, which two headings together comprise the majority of Department for Transport expenditure. As in previous years, this expenditure is therefore broadly allocated on an ‘in’ basis (i.e. the location where the spending took place) in the Treasury analysis.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>It is important to note however that expenditure comparisons on a ‘per-head’ basis (using resident populations) can present a skewed picture of the distribution of benefits for transport generally, and for transport in London particularly. This is because the transport networks in London are routinely used by a very large number of other regions’ residents and it is not just Londoners who are receiving the benefits of the transport expenditure there.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>Even allowing for this point, one would also expect London’s ‘per head’ transport expenditure to be higher than the national average. London provides key international travel gateways for the whole of the country. London is also densely populated with different public transport and infrastructure demands – for example London residents comprise around 15% of the population of England, but London accounts for around half of all bus passenger journeys in England, and almost two-thirds of rail journeys in Great Britain.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-07-08T07:07:45.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386764/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386764/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Public Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the total amount of capital funding per capita on public transport was in each English region in each of the last five financial years.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","4842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386765","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-08","<p>The review of Mersey Tunnel Tolls is being undertaken by the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority. My officials are discussing with them how their review will meet the Government’s aspirations, including ensuring consultation with interested parties both within and adjoining the Combined Authority area.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-07-08T07:26:36.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386765/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386765/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386765/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Mersey Tunnels: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 18 June 2015 to Question 2544, what steps his Department is taking to consult Mersey Tunnel users living outside the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority Area on the toll review.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","4836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386766","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-08","<p>The current recruitment campaign for Maritime Operations Officers within the National Network closes at the beginning of August 2015 and will be followed by the candidate assessment process.</p><p> </p><p>Her Majesty’s Coastguard will continue to, proactively recruit for Coastguard Officers where vacancies exist.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-07-08T11:50:07.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386766/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386766/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Rescue Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to increase the number of people employed in coastguard stations.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","4863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386767","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-08","<p>The Department’s consideration of motor insurance policy concerning vehicles such as these arises from the Vnuk judgement. This case, before the European Court of Justice concerned a man (Mr Vnuk) who was injured when he was knocked off a ladder by a trailer that was attached to a tractor in a barn in Slovenia. The effect of the judgment is that any vehicle that falls within the Motor Insurance Directive’s definition of a vehicle should have a compulsory motor insurance policy. The definition of vehicle in the Directives is very wide. We were disappointed with this judgment.</p><p> </p><p>Officials are in regular dialogue with the European Commission and their EU counterparts about the challenges generated by the Vnuk judgment. This has included dedicated meetings with Commission officials, various exchanges with representatives of other Member States and attending a general meeting of Member States hosted by the Commission in May 2015.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-07-08T11:41:19.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386767/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386767/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with (a) the European Commission and (b) his EU counterparts on insurance cover for (i) tractors, (ii) quad bikes, (iii) ride-on lawnmowers, (iv) motorised wheelchairs and (v) motorised golf caddies.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","4862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386768","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-08","<p>Her Majesty’s Coastguard is currently going through a complex transformation, which involves balancing the progressive implementation of the new Coastguard National Network alongside maintaining service at the remaining Maritime Rescue Coordination Centres, as they await transition.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There has been a significant programme of recruitment and on-going training with a number of officers who are currently trainees becoming fully operational later in the transition.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The current staffing position for both structures is as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p /><p> </p><p /><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>National Network Stations</p><p /> <p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Location</p></td><td><p>Complement</p></td><td><p>Operationally in Post</p></td><td><p>Under Training</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fareham, NMOC</p></td><td><p>95</p></td><td><p>69</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>75</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Aberdeen</p></td><td><p>23</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>22</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Falmouth</p></td><td><p>23</p></td><td><p>18</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>27</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Milford Haven</p></td><td><p>23</p></td><td><p>19</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>27</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Humber</p></td><td><p>23</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>24</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Holyhead</p></td><td><p>23</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>25</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>Pre Transition Maritime Rescue Coordination Centres</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Location</p></td><td><p>Complement</p></td><td><p>Operationally in Post</p></td><td><p>Under Training</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Belfast</p></td><td><p>23</p></td><td><p>18</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>26</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dover</p></td><td><p>27</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>27</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Shetland</p></td><td><p>23</p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Stornoway</p></td><td><p>25</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>26</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-07-08T11:29:48.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386768/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386768/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Rescue Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the level of staff shortage is at each coastguard station.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","4861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386769","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-07","<p>Under the Code of Practice for Ministerial Appointments to Public Bodies April 2012, government departments are required to publicise successful appointments, which will either be on GOV.UK or the appointing body’s website.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-07-07T14:16:32.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386769/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386769/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386769/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Department for Transport: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will place in the Library a list of all public appointments made by his Department between 1 January 2015 and 1 May 2015.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","4972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386770","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-08","<p>The Department holds regular discussions with all franchise train operators about their performance.</p><p> </p><p>In Govia Thameslink Railway’s (GTR) case, since it took over the franchise in September last year, the performance on its Great Northern route has been good. However, performance on the Thameslink route has not been good enough. Senior officials and I have been working with GTR and Network Rail to ensure that the industry identifies and addresses the key issues affecting performance and develops and implements plans to drive improvements in punctuality and reliability for passengers as soon as possible. I have set up regular meetings with industry partners at the most senior level to review its progress against these plans, and recent performance has shown improvement.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has worked with Abellio Greater Anglia and Network Rail to identify the key issues affecting performance and develop long-term plans to improve punctuality and reliability. Abellio Greater Anglia’s recent performance by Public Performance Measure had shown five periods of improvement, and though it has dropped off in the last period for which figures are available, was still broadly on target.</p><p> </p><p>The inner metropolitan services on the West Anglia and Great Eastern Mainline were, as of 31 May this year, devolved to the remit of Transport for London (TfL). Abellio Greater Anglia and the TfL concessionaires are cooperating closely to ensure the standards of service improve.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-07-08T09:15:28.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386770/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386770/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386770/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Railways: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with (a) Abellio Greater Anglia and (b) Govia Thameslink Railway franchise on improving the standards of service.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","4820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386771","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-06","<p>A competition was held in December 2014 for a trial to gather evidence on flexible rail ticketing, which has the potential to provide a better deal for passengers who work part-time or are not daily commuters. Positive expressions of interest were received from seven operators in the South East Flexible Ticketing (SEFT) programme area; we are working with them so they can introduce flexible ticketing products as soon as possible following the roll out of smart ticketing in 2016 and 2017. The Department is also considering a report by Southern Railway, on their flexible ticketing trial, and is discussing with Govia Thameslink Railways and c2c, their franchise, obligations to introduce flexible ticketing products by 30 September 2015 and 31 May 2016 respectively.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","4931","2015-07-06T12:59:04.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386771/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386771/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386771/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Railways: Season Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the results were of his Department's 2014 pilot study of how rail season tickets could be better tailored towards part-time workers.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","4940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386772","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-06","<p>The Invitation To Tender for the TransPennine Express competition was issued in February, formally notifying bidders that they should not assume that Trans-Pennine electrification would be completed for the purposes of their bids.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-07-06T13:05:45.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386772/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386772/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386772/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department notified bidders for the TransPennine Express Rail franchise that rail electrification would not be delivered on the original timetable.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","4937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386773","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-06","<p>The TransPennine Express Invitation to Tender, published on 27 February 2015, did not require bidders to procure electric rolling stock for the trans-Pennine route, on the basis that this would be delivered through changes to the Franchise Agreement that would be negotiated during the new franchise when the detailed plans for electrification were in place.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The franchise specification requires bidders to deliver a substantial increase in capacity into the major cities in the north of England by December 2018.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-07-06T13:17:34.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386773/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386773/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386773/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the effect of the delay to electrification of the Transpennine line on procurement of new rolling stock for the Transpennine franchise.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","4938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386774","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-06","<p>A competition was held in December 2014 for a trial to gather evidence on flexible rail ticketing, which has the potential to provide a better deal for passengers who work part-time or are not daily commuters. Positive expressions of interest were received from seven operators in the South East Flexible Ticketing (SEFT) programme area; we are working with them so they can introduce flexible ticketing products as soon as possible following the roll out of smart ticketing in 2016 and 2017. The Department is also considering a report by Southern Railway, on their flexible ticketing trial, and is discussing with Govia Thameslink Railways and c2c, their franchise, obligations to introduce flexible ticketing products by 30 September 2015 and 31 May 2016 respectively.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","4940","2015-07-06T12:59:04.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386774/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386774/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386774/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Railways: Season Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress his Department has made in discussions with train operating companies on the introduction of flexible rail season ticket options.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","4931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386775","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-06","<p>Departmental officials regularly meet with a range of stakeholders and representatives from across the rail industry, both within the UK and abroad. These discussions can cover a variety of subjects.</p><p> </p>","Derbyshire Dales","Mr Patrick McLoughlin",,"2015-07-06T16:24:50.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386775/answer","Biography information for Sir Patrick McLoughlin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386775/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386775/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Railways: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 29 June 2015 to Question 4164, whether any of the meetings referred to in that Answer which were held outside the UK were on alternative mechanisms for funding rail infrastructure management activities in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","4926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386776","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-06","<p>The Department for Transport encourages broadcasters to adopt a responsible attitude towards driving issues and to use the Media Guide prepared by the Royal Society for the Prevention of Accidents which provides advice. Page 2 of the Guide explains that it is bad practice for a driver to speak to camera without watching the road ahead. The Guide is freely available on-line at <a href="http://www.rospa.com/roadsafety/info/roadmedia.pdf" target="_blank">www.rospa.com/roadsafety/info/roadmedia.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>Rules 148–150 of The Official Highway Code advises drivers to avoid distractions.　 The rules make it clear that drivers must exercise proper control of their vehicle.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>Under sections 2 and 3 of the Road Traffic Act 1988 a person may be charged with the offences of dangerous, careless and inconsiderate driving.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p /><p /> <p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-07-06T14:34:57.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386776/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386776/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386776/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Driving: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the safety implications of drivers being interviewed on film whilst driving.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","4745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386777","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-06","<p>The Government has no plans to place the MPA review reports for 2013-14 in the House of Commons library.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Major Project Authority (MPA) reports are confidential: the reports are designed to provide government and project teams with a frank assessment of a project’s progress and challenges at a point in time.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The assessment is based on a review of documents and candid interviews with project personnel.　 Disclosure of these reports may cause future interviewees for this project or others to be less frank in their exchanges, undermining the integrity and value of the process.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p /><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-07-06T12:30:39.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386777/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386777/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386777/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will place in the Library (a) Major Project Authority reports on High Speed 2 for 2013-14 and (b) an update on such reports for 2015.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","4739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386778","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-06","<p>I have asked the new Chairman of Network Rail, Sir Peter Hendy, to develop a proposal for re-planning the enhancements programme by the autumn. The plan for electrification will be included in that proposal. I would note however that the previous Labour administration managed just ten miles of electrification in 13 years.</p><p> </p>","Derbyshire Dales","Mr Patrick McLoughlin",,"2015-07-06T16:05:21.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386778/answer","Biography information for Sir Patrick McLoughlin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386778/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386778/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Railways: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many miles of track Network Rail plans to electrify during Control Period 5.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","4758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386779","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-06","<p>The most recent estimate of the benefit-cost ratio for Great Western Electrification, dating from February 2015, was 2.36.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The benefit-cost ratio reflects the costs and benefits of electrifying the Great Western network and introducing new electric and bi-mode IEP trains on long distance services and electric multiple units on suburban services.</p><p> </p>","Derbyshire Dales","Mr Patrick McLoughlin",,"2015-07-06T16:08:38.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386779/answer","Biography information for Sir Patrick McLoughlin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386779/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386779/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Great Western Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the benefit-cost ratio for Great Western Main Line electrification was on the most recent date for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","4759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386780","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-07","<p>The Department does not hold information on this. It will be for the developers, working with Network Rail, to undertake any modifications necessary to the Elstree rail tunnels to achieve W10 gauge clearance; and it will be for Network Rail to assess and to schedule the necessary works.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-07-07T14:49:41.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386780/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386780/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386780/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Railways: Radlett","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what information his Department holds on whether either of the Elstree tunnels will need to be closed during the development of the proposed Radlett rail freight terminal.","false","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","4742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386781","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-08","<p>The new search and rescue (SAR) helicopter service operated by Bristow Helicopters Ltd on behalf of Her Majesty’s Coastguard will match the service levels provided by the current military and Coastguard SAR helicopters.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-07-08T10:58:50.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386781/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386781/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386781/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Rescue Services: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what targets and performance measures his Department has specified for levels of service from the company which will operate the search and rescue helicopter service in North West Wales.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","4775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386782","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-08","<p>I have not received any representations from the Welsh Government on the search and rescue helicopter service in north west Wales.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-07-08T11:03:58.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386782/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386782/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386782/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Rescue Services: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what representations he has received from the Welsh Government on the future of the search and rescue helicopter service in North West Wales.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","4776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386783","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-07","<p>The Secretary of State announced on the 25<sup>th</sup> June 2015 that Great Western was his top priority for delivery.　The Secretary of State also described some of the challenges Network Rail is facing. That is why he has asked the new chair of Network Rail to put forward proposals for replanning the enhancement programme.　 The chair is due to report to the Secretary of State in the Autumn and the Secretary of State is not going to pre-empt the outcome of this report.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p /><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-07-07T14:00:46.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386783/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386783/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386783/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Great Western Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department plans to complete the electrification of the Great Western mainline to (a) Bristol, (b) Newport, (c) Cardiff and (d) Swansea.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","4782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386784","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-07","<p>Rural areas will feel the effects of HS2 more than urban areas, where major construction projects are commonplace and properties relatively close to railways or building sites are often shielded from their effects by other buildings and background noise. This is why some of the assistance schemes are directed at rural areas only. However, we have gone beyond what is required by law in order to assist urban owner-occupiers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>The Need to Sell scheme is available to qualifying residents in Wells House Road and Midland Terrace. The owner occupiers of properties on the east side of Wells House Road may be eligible to claim under the Express Purchase scheme. Those affected by the tunnel underneath Wells House Road would be afforded various protections from the impacts from tunnelling, including settlement deeds.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-07-07T14:54:10.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386784/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386784/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386784/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 23 June 2015, Official Report, column 834, whether apart from the need to sell scheme mentioned that residents affected by the High Speed 2 development in Wells House Road and Midland Terrace NW10 will be entitled to support comparable with that being offered through the Rural Zones.","true","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","4779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386785","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-08","<p>Operators must put their customers at the heart of their business and provide the highest standards of service at every retail channel. We welcome the publication of the Code of Practice on Retail Information, the development of which was overseen by the Office of Rail and Road (ORR). The Code gives retailers a clearer understanding of the information they need to provide to passengers to help them choose, buy and use the most appropriate ticket for their journey. The ORR wrote to all train operators in May asking them to assess their compliance with the Code, and is currently reviewing the responses. ORR intends to use this information to target where it thinks further work might be required and will publish an update report in the summer. We will continue to engage with the work the ORR is undertaking and the progress made by train operators to enhance the retail experience for passengers.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-07-08T08:53:37.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386785/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386785/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386785/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the implementation of the Code of Practice on retail information for rail tickets and services, published in March 2015.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","4796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386786","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-08","<p>Bristow Helicopters Ltd is contracted to provide a search and rescue helicopter service covering the whole of the UK for a ten year period. The Government is satisfied that Bristow is fully able to deliver this service as contracted for the entirety of the contract period.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-07-08T11:26:15.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386786/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386786/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386786/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","Rescue Services: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with Bristow Helicopters on that company's contingency plans should it no longer be profitable for it to run the search and rescue service in North West Wales.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","4795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386787","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-08","<p>The Initial Industry Plan (IIP) for the England and Wales rail network will be presented to Government in September 2016. On the basis of the findings of the Anglia Route Study, I anticipate that upgrades to Trowse Swing Bridge will feature in the IIP. During 2017, the Government will provide an indication of which elements of the IIP it wishes to fund from 2019.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-07-08T07:55:10.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386787/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386787/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386787/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-30","East Anglia Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what timetable is in place for the replacement of Trowse Swing Bridge on the Great Eastern Main Line.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","4845"
